@NODE intro "Introduction"


Oner is a program that will keep track of how long you have been connected 
to an online service (e.g. internet service provider) and will update ,
every minute , the total cost you have incurred for that session.

Why the name Oner ?... Well I use dice from the command line and I got
sick of typing   'dcc OntimeCoster.c' so the source was renamed to oner.c
and as sad as it is, I couldn't think of a better name.....
Actually I am trying to justify the terrible name by trying to think of
something it could stand for. 'Orrible No-good Error Ridden ?
Let me know if you have any suggestions...
@ENDNODE

@NODE install "Installation"


The installation of this program is @{"difficult" link pc}.
What you must do is copy the executable (i.e. the program 'oner') 
into whatever directory you want. Starting it is from the command line
or from WB.
The command line option will be useful if you execute it automatically
from within AMITCP's startnet script (for example).

Here is the catch:-
      
      You must edit the @{"oner.config" link config} file and modify it
      to your ISP conditions.

Oner will automatically switch to the current hour's rate on the hour.

So if you don't have a battery backed up clock --- SET THE TIME FIRST ---
or check out my other program on Aminet 'DateHunter' (util/boot).

P.S if you automatically start oner from within AmiTCP's startnet script,
use the command line     run oner   

@ENDNODE

@NODE pc "Why do they sell so many of those things ?"
* I mean installation is difficult for PC clone users.
  (but they have trouble scoring double figures in I.Q tests) 

@ENDNODE

@NODE limits "Limitations"

1 As you might have guessed, this program will not be much good to you
  if your ISP changes their hourly rate on a HALF hour. This is the
  thing that I suspect will cause most people to throw it out.

  If anyone actually likes this program enough to want this, and 
  can't find another program to do a similar job to Oner then
  please E-Mail me and I might have already improved Oner to
  do this. If I haven't then I will try to send a version that is 
  hard coded to his/her ISP conditions.
  
2 This program was written by an Australian , and as local phone
  calls in Australia are not timed, This program has no provision
  for taking into consideration the cost of the call over time.
  As of V1.4 the initial phone connection cost will be included
  into the total. (currently 25 cents for Australia).

  So if your ISP charges $2.00 per hour and your phone company
  charges $4.00 per hour then your total online costs will not
  be accurately represented by this program. This feature would 
  probably not be to hard too implement if enough people want it.
 
  

@ENDNODE

